pr_review_comment_body:
I don't believe this is accurate. For operations on a subscription object, you are correct: it will use the new endpoint. However, for the operations on `ListObject` such as `create`, `all`, `retrieve`, it will [use the URL returned in the `url` parameter](https://github.com/stripe/stripe-python/blob/jacqueline-subs-v1/stripe/resource.py#L314). We aren't changing the subscriptions URL that's returned from the `/v1/customers/cus_foo` endpoint. 

{
  "id": "cus_7j89JgbvIey5zw",
  "object": "customer",
  "subscriptions": {
    "object": "list",
    "data": [
      {
        "id": "sub_7j8BvyTb5vfUef",
        "object": "subscription",
        ...
      }
    ],
    "has_more": false,
    "total_count": 1,
    "url": "/v1/customers/cus_7j89JgbvIey5zw/subscriptions"
  }
}
```

@jirikuncar except that one (good catch BTW), do you see any direct problems with this PR that would prevent you from merging it? 

as @diegodelemos wrote in his comment, https://github.com/inveniosoftware/invenio/issues/3691#issuecomment-355896393 , from what I understand, he considers this PR/branch to be abandoned. From my perspective, it just needs a few simple fixes and it could be committed, so Ubuntu 16.04 users could benefit from easy installation of Invenio. 

@jirikuncar , what are your thoughts on that?

Split this into multiple lines:

    gene: [
        generate_statistic(exp, gene, descriptor, expression_type) 
