    ]

@tseaver `UTC` is [included][1] in `_datetime_from_microseconds` since it uses the [epoch][2]

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/61abd0c8ce00db9784d76589ba7e57c315e32b83/gcloud/_helpers.py#L234
[2]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/61abd0c8ce00db9784d76589ba7e57c315e32b83/gcloud/_helpers.py#L273

Take it or leave it: where possible, I like to use a temporary scope to drop mutability once it is no longer necessary
```
let operation_request = {
  let mut or  = bazel_protos::operations::GetOperationRequest::new();
  or.set_name(result.get_name().to_string());
  or
};
```

A bit cleaner to:
```python
if not is_executable(pex_file_path):
  # create it
return PEX(pex_file_path, interpreter)
```

@eMxyzptlk what about the overhead of this?
I mean `setEtcd` is invoked from a for loop each 10 seconds so if you have just 10 app is 10 additional `etcd` calls just to get the log level.

Why not check the flag periodically from `etcd` (like 30 or 60 seconds) and "store" the value in a local variable instead of the retrieve the value from `etcd`?

I find it easier to read when all of the alternative cases are explicitly handled in else blocks, even if it means a bit of duplication. eg~

```py
    if t_params.get('data') is not None and transaction_params.get('input') is not None:
        if t_params['data'] != transaction_params['input']:
            msg = 'failure to handle this transaction due to both "input: {}" and'
            msg += ' "data: {}" are populated. You need to resolve this conflict.'
            raise AttributeError(msg.format(transaction_params['input'], t_params['data']))
        else:
            return dissoc(t_params, 'input')
    elif t_params.get('data') is None and transaction_params.get('input') is not None:
        remapped_data =  t_params.pop('input')
        return assoc(
            dissoc(t_params, 'input'),
            'data',
            remapped_data,
        )
    else:
        return dissoc(t_params, 'input')
```

The "too complex" message is because the whole class definition is inside the try block. Try moving it out, e.g.

```python
class ColoramaTerminal(...):
    # ...

try:
    from blessings import Terminal as BaseTerminal
except ImportError:
    BaseTerminal = ColoramaTerminal

Why not just:

return {self._resolve_airflow_macros(k): self._resolve_airflow_macros(v) for for k, v in operator_param_value.items()}

to avoid the cast to dict?

This seems dangerous and could lead to false positives, right? Why not use the original version

```
bool operator==(UniqueID a, UniqueID b) {		
  return UNIQUE_ID_EQ(a, b);		
}
```
